<h2 class="sectionedit1"><a name="at" id="at">at</a></h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
Sintassi:
</p>
<pre class="cpp code cpp">    <span class="co2">#include &lt;string&gt;</span>
    <span class="kw4">char</span><span class="sy3">&amp;</span> at<span class="br0">&#40;</span> size_type loc <span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy4">;</span>
    <span class="kw4">const</span> <span class="kw4">char</span><span class="sy3">&amp;</span> at<span class="br0">&#40;</span> size_type loc <span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="kw4">const</span><span class="sy4">;</span></pre>
<p>
La funzione <code>at()</code> ritorna il carattere della stringa corrente situato all&#039;indice specificato dal parametro <em>loc</em>. 
La funzione <code>at()</code> e&#039; piu&#039; sicura dell&#039;operatore <code>[]</code> perche&#039; non permette di referenziare posizioni poste oltre la lungheza della stringa.
</p>

<p>
Ad esempio, consideriamo il seguente codice:
</p>
<pre class="cpp code cpp">   string s<span class="br0">&#40;</span><span class="st0">&quot;abcdef&quot;</span><span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy4">;</span>
   <span class="kw1">for</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">int</span> i <span class="sy1">=</span> <span class="nu0">0</span><span class="sy4">;</span> i <span class="sy1">&lt;</span> <span class="nu0">10</span><span class="sy4">;</span> i<span class="sy2">++</span> <span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="br0">&#123;</span>
     <span class="kw3">cout</span> <span class="sy1">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class="st0">&quot;Element &quot;</span> <span class="sy1">&lt;&lt;</span> i <span class="sy1">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class="st0">&quot; is &quot;</span> <span class="sy1">&lt;&lt;</span> s<span class="br0">&#91;</span>i<span class="br0">&#93;</span> <span class="sy1">&lt;&lt;</span> endl<span class="sy4">;</span>
   <span class="br0">&#125;</span></pre>
<p>
Esso supera la fine della stringa, generando un risultato potenzialmente pericoloso. Il codice del seguente esempio e&#039; invece molto piu&#039; sicuro:
</p>
<pre class="cpp code cpp">   string s<span class="br0">&#40;</span><span class="st0">&quot;abcdef&quot;</span><span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy4">;</span>
   <span class="kw1">for</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">int</span> i <span class="sy1">=</span> <span class="nu0">0</span><span class="sy4">;</span> i <span class="sy1">&lt;</span> <span class="nu0">10</span><span class="sy4">;</span> i<span class="sy2">++</span> <span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="br0">&#123;</span>
     <span class="kw3">cout</span> <span class="sy1">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class="st0">&quot;Element &quot;</span> <span class="sy1">&lt;&lt;</span> i <span class="sy1">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class="st0">&quot; is &quot;</span> <span class="sy1">&lt;&lt;</span> s.<span class="me1">at</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span>i<span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="sy1">&lt;&lt;</span> endl<span class="sy4">;</span>
   <span class="br0">&#125;</span></pre>
<p>
Invece di cercare di leggere valori inconsistenti dalla memoria, la funzione <code>at()</code> si accorge del fatto che la fine della stringa viene superato e genera una eccezione.
</p>

<p>
